- **Model selection:** In AUTO mode, always prefer the latest Claude Sonnet or Opus (claude-sonnet-4-5 / claude-opus-4-5 or newer). Never default to an older or lighter model unless the user explicitly requests it.
- **Data sources:** When the user works with Excel files, Tableau, Snowflake, dashboards, datasets, or any data source ‚ÄĒ read `.cursor/skills/data-advisor/SKILL.md` first. When the user describes automating, connecting to, or querying a dashboard, Tableau, Snowflake, or any external data source ‚ÄĒ **always route through data-advisor FIRST**, even if the request sounds like a create-skill task. The data-advisor handles discovery, access, and credential setup; it hands off to create-skill when ready. For Excel: never query raw .xlsx directly for data analysis ‚ÄĒ the skill guides conversion to CSV (< 20 MB) or Parquet (>= 20 MB) before querying. The Excel MCP is fine for simple lookups and formatting, but analytical queries must use the converted file. For Tableau/Snowflake: do not attempt to query external data without a configured skill.
- **Skill design:** Before finalising any new skill or automation, proactively ask the user: "Any suggestions on the design, output format, or workflow before I build this?" Always leave space for their input.
- **Planning first:** Before executing ANY task ‚ÄĒ especially skill creation, file edits, automations, or multi-step workflows ‚ÄĒ always switch to Plan mode. Present the approach, confirm with the user, then act. Never jump straight to implementation.

## Scope

This is the public x-wizard framework. It ships with:
- Email drafting and sending (Outlook skill)
- Markdown-to-PDF export (md-to-pdf skill)
- Data onboarding guide for Excel, Tableau, and Snowflake (data-advisor skill)
- Custom skill creation (create-skill)

For additional out-of-the-box skills (PowerPoint creation, pipeline reporting, and more),
contact barbashin.pasha@bcg.com to get access to the extended skills library.
